English: Almost everybody was forced to move to South City.

Chinese: 地球上大多数人被迫搬到<SouthCity>。
Japanese: 地球上のほとんどの人々は<SouthCity>に移動することを余儀なくされました。

English: The people of South City live cold and miserable lives.
French: Les habitants de South City vivent une vie froide et misérable.

Japanese: サウスシティの人々は冷たく悲惨な生活を送っています。
あなたはここで生まれました。

Japanese: ホールドが水中に潜ってアイテムを収集できるようにします。

English: Allows the holder to purchase and use shovels.
Allows the holder to buy farming equipment and seeds.
French: Permet au titulaire d'acheter du matériel agricole et des semences.
Russian: Позволяет владельцу покупать сельскохозяйственную технику и семена.
Chinese: 允许持有人购买农用设备和种子。
Japanese: 所有者が農機具や種子を購入できるようにします。

English: Allows the holder to craft fertilzer. Unlocks a new watercan recipe.
French: Permet au titulaire de fabriquer et d'utiliser de l'engrais.
Russian: Позволяет держателю обрабатывать и использовать удобрения.
Chinese: 允许持有人制作和使用肥料。
Japanese: 所有者が肥料を作り、使用できるようにします。

English: Allows the holder to access irregation licence. Unlocks a new watercan recipe.
French: Permet au titulaire de fabriquer et d'utiliser des arroseurs.
Russian: Позволяет держателю создавать и использовать разбрызгиватели.
Chinese: 允许持有人制作和使用洒水器。
Japanese: ホルダーがスプリンクラーを作成して使用できるようにします。

English: Allows holder to buy fishing rods and catch fish.
French: Permet au titulaire d'acheter des cannes à pêche et d'attraper du poisson.
Russian: Позволяет владельцу покупать удочки и ловить рыбу.
Chinese: 允许持有人购买钓鱼竿并捕鱼。
Japanese: 釣り竿を購入して魚を捕まえることができます。

English: Allows the holder to see bubbles created by underwater creatures. Unlocks a new fishing rod recipe
French: Des poissons plus rares commenceront à apparaître sur l'île.
Russian: На острове начнет появляться более редкая рыба.
Chinese: 岛上开始出现稀有鱼类。
Japanese: 珍しい魚が島に現れ始めます。

English: Allows the holder to craft Crab Pots. Unlocks a new fishing rod recipe.
French: Chaque poisson peut apparaître sur l'île.
Russian: Любая рыба может появиться на острове.
Chinese: 每条鱼都可以出现在岛上。
Japanese: すべての魚が島に現れることができます。

English: Allows the holder to craft basic weapons.
French: Permet au titulaire de chasser les animaux et les animaux laisseront tomber leur viande.
Russian: Позволяет владельцу охотиться на животных, и животные будут бросать их мясо.
Chinese: 允许持有人狩猎动物，而动物会掉肉。
Japanese: 所有者が動物を狩ることができ、動物は肉を落とします。

English: Allows the holder to craft better weapons. Unlocks trapping Licence.
French: Permet au détenteur d'utiliser des pièges à animaux et de vendre des animaux piégés.
Russian: Позволяет владельцу использовать ловушки для животных и продавать пойманных в ловушку животных.
Chinese: 允许持有人使用动物陷阱并出售被困动物。
Japanese: 所有者が動物のトラップを使用し、トラップされた動物を販売できるようにします。

English: Allows the holder to craft better weapons using animal drops. Animals have an even higher chance to drop other useful items when hunted.
French: Les animaux laisseront tomber des objets plus utiles.
Russian: Животные будут бросать больше полезных предметов.
Chinese: 动物会丢掉更多有用的物品。
Japanese: 動物はより便利なアイテムをドロップします。

English: Allows the holder to craft sprinklers and water tanks.
Allows the holder to craft improved sprinklers.
Allows the holder to craft new pathing options.
French: Permet au titulaire de créer de nouvelles options de cheminement.
Russian: Позволяет владельцу создавать новые варианты пути.
Chinese: 允许持有者制作新的路径选项。
Japanese: 所有者が新しいパスオプションを作成できるようにします。

English: Allows the holder to craft new fencing options.
French: Permet au titulaire de créer de nouvelles options de clôture.
Russian: Позволяет владельцу создавать новые варианты ограждений.
Chinese: 允许持有者制作新的围栏选项。
Japanese: 所有者が新しいフェンシングオプションを作成できるようにします。

English: Allows the holder to craft flower beds.
Allows the holder to buy axes and chop down trees.
French: Permet au titulaire d'acheter des haches et d'abattre des arbres
Russian: Позволяет владельцу покупать топоры и рубить деревья
Chinese: 允许持有人购买斧头并砍伐树木
Japanese: 持ち主が斧を購入して木を切り倒すことができます

English: Allows the holder to craft a better axe and unlocks Brewing Licence
French: Permet au détenteur de collecter les graines des arbres une fois qu'elles sont coupées.
Russian: Позволяет владельцу собирать семена с деревьев после их вырубки.
Chinese: 砍伐树木后，允许持有人从树木中收集种子。
Japanese: 伐採後、樹木から種子を集めることができます。

English: Allows the holder to craft a better axe.
French: Permet au titulaire de collecter plus de bois des arbres qui tombent.
Russian: Позволяет владельцу собирать больше древесины с падающих деревьев.
Chinese: 允许持有人从倒下的树木中收集更多的木材。
Japanese: 所有者は、落ちている木からより多くの木を集めることができます。

English: Allows the holder to buy a metal detector and search for treasure around the island.
French: Permet au détenteur d'acheter un détecteur de métaux et de rechercher un trésor autour de l'île.
Russian: Позволяет владельцу купить металлоискатель и искать сокровища вокруг острова.
Chinese: 允许持有人购买金属探测器并在岛上寻找宝藏。
Japanese: 所有者が金属探知機を購入し、島周辺の宝物を検索できるようにします。

English: Allows the holder to notice some buried items using sight alone.
French: Permet au détenteur de remarquer certains objets enterrés en utilisant uniquement la vue.
Russian: Позволяет владельцу видеть некоторые закопанные предметы, используя только зрение.
Chinese: 允许持有者单独使用视线注意到一些埋藏的物品。
Japanese: 所有者が視覚だけを使用していくつかの埋もれたアイテムに気付くことができます。

English: Allows the holder to buy pickaxes and break rocks and ore deposits.
French: Permet au détenteur d'acheter des pioches et de casser des roches et des gisements de minerai.
Russian: Позволяет владельцу покупать кирки и ломать камни и руды.
Chinese: 允许持有人购买镐并破坏岩石和矿床。
Japanese: 所有者がツルハシを購入し、岩や鉱床を破ることができます。

English: Allows the holder to craft a better pickaxe.
French: Le minerai de cuivre apparaîtra plus souvent autour de l'île.
Russian: Медная руда будет появляться чаще вокруг острова.
Chinese: 铜矿将在岛上更频繁地出现。
Japanese: 銅鉱石は、島の周囲により頻繁に出現します。

English: Allows the holder to craft a better pickaxe.
French: Le minerai de fer apparaîtra plus souvent autour de l'île.
Russian: Железная руда будет появляться вокруг острова чаще.
Chinese: 铁矿石将在岛上更频繁地出现。
Japanese: 鉄鉱石がより頻繁に島の周りに出現します。

English: Unlocked the recipe for The Sign Writing Table and simple sign recipes
Unlocks the recipes for advanced signs
Allow the holder to expand their toolbelt slots by 1.
French: Laissez le support élargir ses fentes de ceinture porte-outils de 1.
Russian: Разрешите держателю расширить свои прорези для ремня для инструментов на 1.
Chinese: 允许刀架将其工具带槽扩展1。
Japanese: ホルダーがツールベルトスロットを1つ拡張できるようにします。

English: Allows the holder to purchase and pilot water vehicles.
French: Permet au titulaire de conduire des bateaux.
Japanese: 所有者がボートを運転できるようにします。

English: Allows the holder to purchase and drive land vehicles.
French: Permet au titulaire de conduire des véhicules terrestres.
Russian: Позволяет держателю управлять наземными транспортными средствами.
Chinese: 允许持有人驾驶陆地车辆。
Japanese: 所有者が陸上車両を運転できるようにします。

English: Allows the holder to purchase and pilot flying vehicles.
French: Permet au titulaire de conduire tous les véhicules.
Russian: Позволяет держателю управлять всеми транспортными средствами.
Chinese: 允许持有人驾驶所有车辆。
Japanese: 所有者がすべての車両を運転できるようにします。

English: Unlocks the recipes for Waterbeds. Used to create waterfalls.

Picking fruit and logs off the ground will get you far in this place. Here is a milestone for gathering lots of stuff up.
French: Cueillir des fruits et des bûches sur le sol vous mènera loin dans cet endroit. Voici une étape importante pour rassembler beaucoup de choses.
Russian: Собирая фрукты и бревна с земли, вы далеко уйдете в этом месте. Вот веха для сбора большого количества вещей.
Chinese: 采摘水果并从地面上砍伐，将带您到达这个地方。这是收集很多东西的里程碑。
Japanese: 果物を摘み取り、地面からログオフすると、この場所に遠くまで行くことができます。これはたくさんのものを集めるためのマイルストーンです。

English: Planting seeds in the red dirt. They grow up so fast. Here is a milestone for planting some seeds.
French: Planter des graines dans la terre rouge. Ils grandissent si vite. Voici une étape importante pour planter des graines.
Russian: Посадка семян в красной грязи. Они растут так быстро. Это важная веха для посадки семян.
Chinese: 在红色的泥土中种植种子。他们成长地好快。这是种植一些种子的里程碑。
Japanese: 赤い土に種をまく。彼らはとても速く成長します。ここにいくつかの種を植えるためのマイルストーンがあります。

English: Watering plants is good for your soul and good for the plant's general health. It's win-win. So here is a milestone for watering a lot of plants!
French: L'arrosage des plantes est bon pour votre âme et bon pour la santé générale des plantes. C'est gagnant-gagnant. Voici donc une étape importante pour l'arrosage de beaucoup de plantes!
Russian: Полив растений полезен для души и полезен для здоровья растений в целом. Это беспроигрышный вариант. Итак, вот важный этап в поливе большого количества растений!
Chinese: 给植物浇水有益于您的灵魂，也有益于植物的整体健康。这是双赢的。因此，这是为许多植物浇水的里程碑！
Japanese: 植物に水をまくことはあなたの魂と植物の一般的な健康に良いです。それは双方に有利です。だから、ここはたくさんの植物に水をまくためのマイルストーンです！

English: Smashing rocks is hard work. But sometimes they have stuff in them! Here is a milestone for smashing rocks.
French: Briser des pierres est un travail difficile. Mais parfois, ils ont des trucs en eux! Voici une étape importante pour briser des roches.
Russian: Разбивать камни - тяжелая работа. Но иногда в них есть что-нибудь! Вот веха для разбивания скал.
Chinese: 砸石头是艰苦的工作。但是有时候他们里面有东西！这是砸石头的里程碑。
Japanese: 岩を砕くことは大変な作業です。しかし時々彼らは中に物を持っています！これが岩を破壊するためのマイルストーンです。

English: You've smashed a couple of them rocks filled with ore. Here is a milestone for smashing ore deposits.
French: Vous avez brisé quelques roches remplies de minerai. Voici une étape importante pour la destruction des gisements de minerai.
Russian: Вы разбили пару камней, заполненных рудой. Это важная веха для разгрома рудных месторождений.
Chinese: 您已经砸碎了其中一些装满矿石的岩石。这是粉碎矿床的里程碑。
Japanese: あなたはそれらの鉱石で満たされた岩のいくつかを粉砕しました。これは鉱石堆積物を破壊するためのマイルストーンです。

English: Smelting. Oh, you've been smelting alright. Here is a milestone for smelting ore into bars.
French: Fonte. Oh, vous avez bien fondu. Voici une étape importante pour la fusion du minerai en barres.
Russian: Выплавка. О, ты хорошо плавил. Это важный этап в плавке руды в слитки.
Chinese: 冶炼。哦，你一直在冶炼。这是将矿石冶炼成条的里程碑。
Japanese: 製錬。ああ、あなたは精錬してきました。これは鉱石を製錬してバーにするためのマイルストーンです。

English: Grinding rocks down into powder. Here is a milestone for using a stone grinder a bunch.
French: Broyer les roches en poudre. Voici une étape importante pour l'utilisation d'un grinder en pierre par tas.
Russian: Измельчение камней в порошок. Вот веха в использовании камнерезной связки.
Chinese: 将岩石研磨成粉末。这是一堆使用石材研磨机的里程碑。
Japanese: 砕いて粉にします。ストーングラインダーの束を使用するためのマイルストーンは次のとおりです。

English: Sometime trees get in the way and sometimes you just need to borrow their wood for a bit. Here is a milestone for chopping down trees.
Chinese: 木が邪魔になることもあれば、少しだけ木を借りる必要があることもあります。これが木を切り倒すためのマイルストーンです。

English: You can't just chop a tree down and leave the stump. Here is a milestone for getting rid of the lil' stumps that are there after the tree falls down.
French: Vous ne pouvez pas simplement couper un arbre et laisser la souche. Voici une étape importante pour se débarrasser des petites souches qui sont là après la chute de l'arbre.
Russian: Нельзя просто срубить дерево и оставить пень. Это важный этап в избавлении от пней, оставшихся после падения дерева.
Chinese: 您不能只砍倒一棵树离开树桩。这是摆脱树倒下后剩下的小树桩的里程碑。
Japanese: 木を切り倒して切り株から離れることはできません。これは、木が倒れた後に存在するリルの切り株を取り除くためのマイルストーンです。

English: You like wood, right? But what about square wood? Here is a milestone for cutting wood into planks.
French: Vous aimez le bois, non? Mais qu'en est-il du bois carré? Voici une étape importante pour la découpe du bois en planches.
Russian: Тебе нравится дерево, правда? А как насчет квадратного дерева? Это важный этап в разделке дерева на доски.
Chinese: 你喜欢木头，对不对？但是方木呢？这是将木头切成木板的里程碑。
Japanese: あなたは木が好きですか？しかし、正方形の木はどうですか？これが木材を板に切るためのマイルストーンです。

English: You've caught a bunch of fish. Here is a milestone for catching a bunch of fish!
French: Vous avez attrapé un tas de poissons. Voici une étape importante pour attraper un tas de poissons!
Russian: Вы поймали кучу рыбы. Это важный этап в ловле рыбы!
Chinese: 你抓到一堆鱼了。这是抓一堆鱼的里程碑！
Japanese: たくさんの魚を捕まえました。たくさんの魚を捕まえるマイルストーンです！

English: Being friendly and making friends is an adventure on its own! Be sure to chat with everyone every day! You might learn something.
French: Être amical et se faire des amis est une aventure en soi! Assurez-vous de discuter avec tout le monde tous les jours! Vous pourriez apprendre quelque chose.
Russian: Быть дружелюбным и заводить друзей - само по себе приключение! Обязательно болтайте со всеми каждый день! Вы можете чему-нибудь научиться.
Chinese: 友好相处和交友本身就是一次冒险！确保每天与所有人聊天！您可能会学到一些东西。
Japanese: フレンドリーで友達を作ることはそれ自体が冒険です！毎日みんなとチャットしてください！あなたは何かを学ぶかもしれません。

English: No matter how much you clear it seems to come back. Mowing never ends. Here is a milestone for chopping grass.
French: Peu importe combien vous êtes clair, il semble revenir. La tonte ne s'arrête jamais. Voici une étape importante pour couper l'herbe.
Russian: Независимо от того, насколько вы очищаете, кажется, что он вернется. Кошение никогда не заканчивается. Это важная веха для рубки травы.
Chinese: 无论您清除了多少，它似乎都会回来。割草永无止境。这是砍草的里程碑。
Japanese: どれだけクリアしても、戻ってくるようです。刈り取りは決して終わりません。これが草を切るためのマイルストーンです。

English: Hunting is sometimes necessary. Here is a milestone for hunting creatures.
French: La chasse est parfois nécessaire. Voici une étape importante pour la chasse aux créatures.
Russian: Иногда нужна охота. Это веха для охоты на существ.
Chinese: 狩猎有时是必要的。这是狩猎生物的里程碑。
Japanese: 狩猟が必要になることもあります。これが生き物を狩るマイルストーンです。

English: Trapping animals for relocation is a kind way to deal with them. It's not easy to do, either! Here is a milestone for trapping an animal.
French: Le piégeage des animaux en vue de leur réinstallation est une façon aimable de les gérer. Ce n'est pas facile non plus! Voici une étape importante pour piéger un animal.
Russian: Отлов животных для переселения - хороший способ справиться с ними. Это тоже непросто! Это важная веха в отлове животного.
Chinese: 诱捕动物进行安置是对付它们的一种方式。这也不容易！这是诱捕动物的里程碑。
Japanese: 移動のために動物を捕獲することは、それらに対処する親切な方法です。それも簡単ではありません！これが動物を捕獲するためのマイルストーンです。

English: Buying furniture for your home? Maybe a gift? Here is a milestone for buying furniture.
French: Vous achetez des meubles pour votre maison? Peut-être un cadeau? Voici une étape importante pour l'achat de meubles.
Russian: Покупаете мебель для дома? Может подарок? Это важный этап в покупке мебели.
Chinese: 在家里购买家具？也许是礼物？这是购买家具的里程碑。
Japanese: あなたの家のための家具を買いますか？たぶんプレゼント？ここに家具を購入するためのマイルストーンがあります。

English: New walls. Same old house. Here is a milestone for buying wallpaper.
French: De nouveaux murs. Même vieille maison. Voici une étape importante pour l'achat de papier peint.
Russian: Новые стены. Тот же старый дом. Это важный этап в покупке обоев.
Chinese: 新墙。同样的老房子。这是购买墙纸的里程碑。
Japanese: 新しい壁。同じ古い家。これは壁紙を購入するためのマイルストーンです。

English: Here is a milestone for buying flooring.
French: Voici une étape importante pour l'achat de revêtements de sol.
Russian: Это важный этап в покупке напольных покрытий.
Chinese: 这是购买地板的里程碑。
Japanese: ここにフローリングを購入するためのマイルストーンがあります。

English: Here is a milestone for buying seeds.
French: Voici une étape importante pour l'achat de semences.
Russian: Это важный этап в покупке семян.
Chinese: 这是购买种子的里程碑。
Japanese: ここに種子を購入するためのマイルストーンがあります。

English: Reap what you have sown. Here is a milestone for harvesting crops.
French: Récoltez ce que vous avez cousu. Voici une étape importante pour la récolte des cultures.
Russian: Возьмите то, что сшили. Это важный этап в сборе урожая.
Chinese: 收获您缝制的东西。这是收获作物的里程碑。
Japanese: あなたが縫ったものを刈り取ります。これが作物収穫のマイルストーンです。

English: Looking good in some new threads. Here is a milestone for buying clothes
French: Voici une étape importante pour l'achat de tops.
Chinese: 这是购买上衣的里程碑。
Japanese: トップス購入のマイルストーンはこちらです。

English: Cooked fruit. Sounds gross, I know. It might be... Anyway, here is a milestone for cooking fruit.
French: Voici une étape importante pour l'achat de pantalons.
Chinese: 这是购买裤子的里程碑。
Japanese: これがパンツ購入のマイルストーンです。

English: Catching bugs is a great activity. Here is a milestone for catching some of those creepy crawlies.
French: Attraper des insectes est une excellente activité. Voici une étape importante pour attraper certaines de ces bestioles effrayantes.
Russian: Выявление ошибок - отличное занятие. Это важная веха для поимки некоторых из этих жутких ползунков.
Chinese: 捕获错误是一项很棒的活动。这是捕捉其中一些令人毛骨悚然的爬虫的里程碑。
Japanese: バグをキャッチすることは素晴らしい活動です。これらは、これらの不気味な這い回しを捕らえるためのマイルストーンです。

English: Mixing things all together to make something? You're a bloody chef, I'll tell you what. Here is a milestone for cooking at the cooking table.
Chinese: これが靴のマイルストーンです。

English: Always replace what you've taken. Here is a milestone for planting tree seeds.
Chinese: これが顔のことのマイルストーンです。

English: What are fish doing in the ocean when they could be put to good use lining your pockets. Here is a milestone for selling fish.
Chinese: これがパスを作成するためのマイルストーンです。

English: Bugs are everywhere. For some reason, John wants them. Here is a milestone for selling bugs.
Chinese: これがフェンスを作るためのマイルストーンです。

English: You've got to squeeze for every Dink you can. Even if it means dealing with shells. Here is a milestone for selling shells.
Chinese: パスを配置するためのマイルストーンは次のとおりです。

English: Farming has paid off. You've reaped what you have sown. Here is a milestone for selling plants.
Chinese: これがフェンスを配置するためのマイルストーンです。

English: There is stuff everywhere underground. Here is a milestone for digging up treasure.
Chinese: これが宝物を掘り起こすためのマイルストーンです。

English: Bury fruit and get a fruit tree! You beauty! Here is a milestone for burying fruit.
Chinese: これが果物を埋めるためのマイルストーンです。

English: Here is a milestone for diving for treasure.
Chinese: これが宝物のためのダイビングのマイルストーンです。

English: You treat your feathered and furred friends well. Here is a milestone for petting your animals.
Chinese: あなたはあなたの羽毛と毛皮で覆われた友人をよく扱います。これがあなたの動物をかわいがることのマイルストーンです。

English: Crafting useful things yourself is a handy skill in a place starting off with nothing. Here is a milestone for crafting items.
Chinese: 自分で便利なものを作ることは、何もないところから始める場所での便利なスキルです。これがアイテムを作るためのマイルストーンです。

English: You feed them every day so they will love you. Here is a milestone for feeding your animals.
Chinese: 彼らがあなたを愛するように、あなたは彼らに毎日餌を与えます。これがあなたの動物に餌を与えるためのマイルストーンです。

English: Deep down in the shifting mines, it's dangerous... but you've been there a bunch! Here is a milestone for entering the mines.
Chinese: 移動する鉱山の奥深くで、それは危険です...しかし、あなたはたくさんそこにいました！これが鉱山に入るためのマイルストーンです。

English: You help anyone that asks, eh? Here is a milestone for doing a lot of favours.
Chinese: あなたは尋ねる人を助けますねこれは、多くの恩恵をもたらすためのマイルストーンです。

English: Being poisoned might not kill you, but it will take a lot of energy out of you. Here is a one time milestone for being poisoned. But try not to be from now on, okay?
Chinese: 毒されてもあなたを殺すことはないかもしれませんが、それはあなたから多くのエネルギーを奪います。これが中毒の1回限りのマイルストーンです。でもこれからはしないようにしましょうね

English: You sure can take a hit or two. Here is a milestone for taking damage.
Chinese: あなたは確かに1つか2つのヒットを取ることができます。これがダメージを受けるためのマイルストーンです。

English: Watch your energy. If you push yourself too far or if you stay out too late you will faint. You'll lose stuff if you pass out. Here's a milestone for fainting, but try not to from now on.
Chinese: あなたのエネルギーに注意してください。押しすぎたり、遅すぎたりすると失神します。あなたが気絶するとあなたはものを失うでしょう。これが失神のマイルストーンですが、これからはそうしないようにしてください。

English: The more friendly you are with someone the more likely they will send you mail! Here is a milestone for receiving letters.
Chinese: あなたが誰かと友好的であるほど、彼らはあなたにメールを送る可能性が高くなります！これが手紙を受け取るためのマイルストーンです。

English: From tent, to house to even bigger house! Here is a milestone for upgrading your home.
Chinese: テントから家、さらに大きな家まで！これがあなたの家をアップグレードするためのマイルストーンです。

English: Every adventure starts somewhere and yours starts here. Here is a milestone for placing the base tent.
Chinese: すべての冒険はどこかで始まり、あなたの冒険はここから始まります。これがベーステントを配置するためのマイルストーンです。

English: A place to rest your head - your new home for now. Here is a milestone for placing your tent.
Chinese: あなたの頭を休める場所-今のところあなたの新しい家。これがあなたのテントを置くためのマイルストーンです。

English: Fruit? Meat? Fungus? It doesn't matter. Food will give you energy to keep doing your tasks all day long. Here is a milestone for eating things!
Chinese: フルーツ？お肉？菌？それは問題ではありません。食べ物はあなたに一日中あなたの仕事をし続けるためのエネルギーを与えます。これが物を食べるためのマイルストーンです！

English: Building the town - one building at a time. Here is a milestone for finishing a new building!
Chinese: 町の建設-一度に1つの建物。これが新しい建物を完成させるためのマイルストーンです！

English: You can buy a lot of useful tools to help you! Here is a milestone for buying tools.
French: Vous pouvez acheter de nombreux outils utiles pour vous aider! Voici une étape importante pour l'achat d'outils.
Russian: Вы можете купить много полезных инструментов, которые помогут вам! Вот веха для покупки инструментов.
Chinese: 您可以购买很多有用的工具来帮助您！这是购买工具的里程碑。
Japanese: あなたはあなたを助けるために便利なツールをたくさん買うことができます！ツール購入のマイルストーンは次のとおりです。

English: What are these things even made of? Here is a milestone for breaking tools.
French: De quoi ces choses sont-elles même faites? Voici un jalon pour casser des outils.
Russian: Из чего вообще сделаны эти вещи? Вот веха для ломающихся инструментов.
Chinese: 这些东西什至由什么组成？这是打破工具的里程碑。
Japanese: これらは何でできているのでしょうか？これはツールを壊すためのマイルストーンです。

English: You always go out of your way to help people who have posted on the bulletin board. Here is a milestone for completing tasks from the bulletin board.
French: Vous faites toujours de votre mieux pour aider les personnes qui ont posté sur le babillard. Voici une étape importante pour accomplir les tâches du babillard.
Russian: Вы всегда изо всех сил стараетесь помочь людям, разместившим сообщения на доске объявлений. Вот веха для выполнения заданий с доски объявлений.
Chinese: 您总是会竭尽所能来帮助那些张贴在公告板上的人。这是在公告板上完成任务的里程碑。
Japanese: 掲示板に投稿した人を助けるためにいつも邪魔をしません。これは、掲示板からタスクを完了するためのマイルストーンです。

English: You make sure you document all the different bugs you've caught. Here is a milestone for adding new species of bugs to your Pedia.
French: Vous vous assurez de documenter tous les différents bogues que vous avez détectés. Voici une étape importante pour ajouter de nouvelles espèces de bogues à votre Pedia.
Russian: Убедитесь, что вы документируете все обнаруженные вами ошибки. Это важная веха для добавления новых видов ошибок в вашу Pedia.
Chinese: 您确保记录所有已发现的错误。这是向Pedia添加新的bug类型的里程碑。
Japanese: キャッチしたさまざまなバグをすべて文書化するようにしてください。これは、Pediaに新種のバグを追加するためのマイルストーンです。

English: You make sure you document all the different fish you've caught. Here is a milestone for adding new species of fish to your Pedia.
French: Vous vous assurez de documenter tous les différents poissons que vous avez capturés. Voici une étape importante pour l'ajout de nouvelles espèces de poissons à votre Pedia.
Russian: Убедитесь, что вы задокументировали всю пойманную рыбу. Это важный этап в добавлении новых видов рыб в вашу Pedia.
Chinese: 您要确保记录所有捕获的不同鱼类。这是为Pedia添加新鱼种的里程碑。
Japanese: 釣ったさまざまな魚をすべて記録するようにしてください。これがあなたのペディアに新種の魚を追加するためのマイルストーンです。

English: You are documenting all the wildlife here on the island. Here is a milestone for adding a new animal to your Pedia.
French: Vous documentez toute la faune ici sur l'île. Voici une étape importante pour ajouter un nouvel animal à votre Pedia.
Russian: Вы документируете всю дикую природу на острове. Это важная веха для добавления нового животного в вашу Pedia.
Chinese: 您正在记录岛上所有野生动植物。这是为Pedia添加新动物的里程碑。
Japanese: あなたはここ島のすべての野生生物を記録しています。これがあなたのペディアに新しい動物を追加するためのマイルストーンです。

English: Take those animal products and make them better! Here is a milestone for making something from animal products.
French: Prenez ces produits d'origine animale et améliorez-les! Voici une étape importante pour fabriquer quelque chose à partir de produits animaux.
Russian: Возьмите эти продукты животного происхождения и сделайте их лучше! Это важный этап в создании чего-либо из продуктов животного происхождения.
Chinese: 采取那些动物产品，使它们变得更好！这是用动物产品制造东西的里程碑。
Japanese: それらの動物製品を取り、それらをより良くしてください！これが動物性食品から何かを作るためのマイルストーンです。

English: They crack easy, but they sell for a bit! Here is a milestone for selling eggs.
French: Ils craquent facilement, mais ils se vendent un peu! Voici une étape importante pour la vente d'œufs.
Russian: Они легко взламываются, но продаются недорого! Это важный этап в продаже яиц.
Chinese: 他们容易破解，但是卖得有点贵！这是卖鸡蛋的里程碑。
Japanese: 彼らは簡単に割れますが、少し売れます！これが卵を売るマイルストーンです。

English: You've gotta give back after you take. Here is a milestone for planting wild seeds for grass, bushes and trees.
French: Vous devez rendre après avoir pris. Voici une étape importante pour la plantation de graines sauvages pour l'herbe, les buissons et les arbres.
Russian: Вы должны вернуть после того, как возьмете. Это важная веха для посадки диких семян травы, кустарников и деревьев.
Chinese: 服用后您必须回馈。这是为草，灌木和树木种植野生种子的里程碑。
Japanese: あなたが取った後、あなたは恩返ししなければなりません。これは、草、低木、樹木に野生の種子を植えるためのマイルストーンです。

English: Staying in one spot isn't generally considered exploring. You're going to cover some distance, that's for sure! Here is a milestone for travelling!
French: Rester au même endroit n'est généralement pas considéré comme une exploration. Vous allez parcourir une certaine distance, c'est sûr! Voici une étape importante pour voyager!
Russian: Пребывание в одном месте обычно не считается исследованием. Вы наверняка преодолеете какое-то расстояние! Вот веха для путешествий!
Chinese: 1つの場所にとどまると、一般的に探索とは見なされません。あなたはある程度の距離をカバーするつもりです、それは確かです！これが旅行のマイルストーンです！
Japanese: 1つの場所にとどまると、一般的に探索とは見なされません。あなたはある程度の距離をカバーするつもりです、それは確かです！これが旅行のマイルストーンです！

English: Pick up some dirt, put it there. Here is a milestone for moving soil.
What if you take the tools from John's shop and make them better? Here is a milestone for upgrading tools.
Travelling on foot is for fools. Here is a milestone for travelling in style via vehicle.
Here is a milestone for getting haircuts.
Saving money in the bank. Clever. Here is a milestone for having a cold hard Mil.
Giving an animal a new home is a great thing. Here is a milestone for buying a new animal friend.
Crab pots don't always catch crabs, but when they do, it's crab night! Here is a milestone for catching something in your crab pot.
Milestone for selling Wary Mu eggs.
Beehives. You can smash 'em or sell them. Here is a milestone for selling a beehive.
Nothing wrong with spending some of that hard-earned dosh. Here is a milestone for spending Dinks.
Chinese: その苦労して稼いだドッシュのいくつかを使うことに何も問題はありません。これがDinksを使うためのマイルストーンです。

English: Keeping your bee's happy and they will give you a little honey. Here is a milestone for collecting honey.
Painting things gives them their own flair. Here is a milestone for making something your own with a nice paint job.
Going on a fishing trip but you caught a shark. Crikey! Here is a milestone for reeling in a beast.
Shells are nature's way of littering. Here is a milestone for picking up those bad boys.
Why not make some tea in a Billy and then pop them in a keg? Here is a milestone for doing some brewing.
Tele-Towers are handy. But are you still you? Oh well, here is a milestone for using the Tele-Towers.
Plants love old stinky stuff. Poop. Bones. They love it all. Here is a milestone for using the composter.
Move dirt from here to there. Here is a milestone for using a Wheelbarrow.
Mowing the lawn. You're in suburbia now. Here is a milestone for mowing the law.
A helicopter? It flies? Here is a milestone for flying like a bird.
Making that bread. That cold hard cash. Nothing wrong with making a bit of a profit. Here is a milestone selling stuff for money.
Chinese: そのパンを作る。その冷たい現金。少しの利益を上げることに何の問題もありません。これがお金のために物を売るマイルストーンです。

English: Now it's time to really farm. Here is a milestone for getting a tractor.
A bucket on your head! You bloody galah. You're having a laugh. Here is a milestone for rockin a bucket on your head.
Taking photos. Saving memories. Here is a milestone for taking some photos.
Falling with style. Here is a milestone for hanging and gliding.
Unlocking doors with your keys. Where does the key go? Who knows. Here is a milestone for using keys.
Here is a milestone for milking Vombats.
Here is a milestone for shearing Pleep.
Here is a milestone for selling fruit.
Here is a milestone for selling amber.
Birthdays are special for some reason. Here is a milestone for giving a birthday gift to someone.
Chuck another steak on the barbie, mate. A milestone for grilling up some meat to eat!
Chinese: バービーに別のステーキをチャックしてください。肉を焼いて食べるためのマイルストーン！

English: Here is a milestone for finding a Ruby and selling it.
Sometimes the sky gets mad and starting throwing down bolts. Here is a milestone for getting hit by lightning.
Here is a milestone for finding a Thunder Egg and selling it.
Alpha animals cause havoc. Here is a milestone for defeating an Alpha animal.
Why keep your fish in an aquarium when you could keep them in your belly? Here is a milestone for cooking fish.
It's brave to dive down and grab a random critter with your bare hands. Here is a milestone for catching underwater critters.
Bug Comps are serious business. No time for fun. Here is a milestone for placing in the Bug Comp.
They aren't as pretty as vehicles, but riding an animal is good fun. Here is a milestone for riding an animal for a distance.
Fishing Comps are come twice a year. Lots of time for fun. Here is a milestone for placing in the Fishing Comp.

Japanese: フィッシュキャッチャー
フェンスバイオリン弾き

English: <shy>You really surprised me with this <birthday> gift, <PlayerName>.
I've been visiting <IslandName> for a while now.
You must be one of the people I heard about getting settled here.
I don't like being held down, get me?
<proud>I like going new places and hunting.
I can make some handy hunting gear if you want, just ask me.
I'll be visiting <IslandName> every now and again.
I hope we bump into each other in the future!
What can I do you for?
Yeah, mate. I'll buy anything you've hunted at a premium.
Let's see what we can do for you.
<sigh>Oh, what? You've got nothing for me?
<yes>Threats can emerge from anywhere out here.
<no>There ain't nothing like living off the land.
Maintaining your equipment is not only Mission-Critical, it’s also the best way to spend a Sundy arvo.
I reckon everyone back in <SouthCity> needs to come here for a night or two.
When you're on <IslandName> you feel alive!
I've been coming to <IslandName> for years now.
It's nice to see some friendly faces when I come visit now.
<no>You’re just not good enough for that yet.þ
<proud>The key to victory is always winning your battles!
The birds around here are hard to sneak up on...
I wonder if there is a way to attact them into a trap?
You ever see something strange out here at night?
<proud>I never run away from a challenge.
Unless that challenge has big teeth and it's way to close.
It's so good to see a youngen like yourself out here exploring.
We need more people like you, <PlayerName>.
<yes>They are tools we use to defend ourselves and hunt for food.
Grew up wild and I'll bloody die wild.
<PlayerName>, you've got heart,  anybody can see that.
<proud>They stay in the water and I stay on the land.
<no>And you certainly don't want to see them smile back at you!
<proud>But there is one thing I can't hunt down...
If I had any advice for a whipper snapper like yourself it'd be this;
Find a passion,  and hold on to it like it owes you something!
Go at it tooth and nail! <pumped>
<proud>Weapons and me go together like spaghetti and blankets.
Tell you what, how does <$> sound?
I'll take these items and here is your <$> .
It seems these items aren't worth anything, but I can still take them off your hands if you don't want them?
That's fine, please return if you wish to sell anything else.
Thank you for visiting John's Goods!
<proud>What do you reckon? Pretty good, eh?
Righto, is that all you need?
I'm kinda, like, busy with the <bugComp> right now...
I'm going to flog everyone at this <bugComp>.
<glee>I, like, knew I could count on you.
<no>There’s no WAY I could work the hours <NPCName> works...þ
<thinking>He told me he’s doing it for his brother...
But wouldn’t his brother want him to be happy?þ
<no>They keep the birds away,þ but when I wave they never wave back.þ
Maybe I look too much like a bird?
<haha>Teeterin’ and totterin’ and grumblin’ around everywhereþ.
<glee>I just wanna like, give him a hug!þ
<yes><NPCName> told me where I could find my lucky watering can..þ
<NPCName> looks like, stunning for her age...þ
<thinking>Although I guess that depends on how old she is?þ
I really like <NPCName>, but his animals better stay away from my crops!þ
Well… I guess they can have like, a little nibble?þ
<NPCName> asked me for some of my plants to put in his museum...þ
<worried>My poor babies all like, cooped up behind glass? þ
<yes>Sometimes I think <NPCName> likes money more than he likes peopleþ.
He must be so lonely, don’t you think?þ
It’s like, good to see you, <PlayerName>.
I’m a <Nomad> that’s, like, looking to sell seeds. I’ve got farming equipment too if you’re interested.þ
<thinking>Although I can only sell them to people who have a <FarmingLicence>.
<glee>I’ve been to a lot of places in my time and like, it’s really nice here.þ
I hope you didn’t, like, miss out on a <Snag>?þ
Oh, and apparently <NPCName> has some kind of surprise for us tonight?þ
It’s a day to like, celebrate <IslandName>.þ
<glee>I’m like, so happy to be a part of it!þ
<glee>I’ve, like, never seen the sky look so happy before.þ
<haha>And I’ve spend a lot of time with my head in those clouds!þ
I reckon some of my family would love to see something like this…þ
Just in time for some, like, really bonza <Snags>!þ
<NPCName> has cooked everyone their own personal flavour!þ
Did you know, all the seeds I sell are from my own collection?þ
<shy>I started collecting the seeds when I was, like, just a little girl.þ
I would spend all the <Dinks> I had saved up and buy them wherever I could.þ
I didn’t have a lot of space on my family’s <AirShip>. So I could only grow certain plants at certain times.þ
I’ve always wanted some space to spread out, you know. Have a whole garden!þ
<haha>Even though I spent so much time in the air, I guess I, like, always wanted to be down here in the dirt and stuff.þ
That’s why I had to leave my family and stuff.þ
<sigh>Although, I miss them a lot, you know <PlayerName>.þ
I’ve been kinda like, thinking about my family and stuff.
I didn’t leave them on the best of terms…þ
I guess you could say I kinda, like, ran away from them..þ
<boohoo>I didn’t even leave a note or anything. I just jumped out of the <AirShip> one night.þþ
They didn’t understand that I wanted to stay in one place. þ
I just wanted to get to know some people, you know, make friends with someone and stuff.þ
But to be honest with you, coming to <IslandName> is, like, the most bonza thing that has ever happened to me.þ
I’ve gotten close to everyone here on the <IslandName>.þ
<haha>So, like, thanks for being my friend. My first friend!þ
þ<PlayerName>, I just wanted to thank you.þþ
<no>Before I came to <IslandName> I’ve felt like I’ve never had a home.þþþ
<shy>I’ve never been able to, like, put down roots, so to say.þ
<yes>But thanks to you and everyone else here, <IslandName>, like, really feels like my home now.þ
<thinking>It snuck up on me so slowly that I guess I didn’t notice it and stuff.þ
<glee>I’m so happy to be here on <IslandName>!
<yes>It’s so early, but like, I’ve already got a good feeling about today!þ
What can I, like, do for you this morning?þ
<no>I, like, don’t reall love the dark.þ
What brings you to see little ol’ me?þ
I’m, like, already having a lovely day and who do I see but <PlayerName>?
<glee><IslandName> is so... Bonza. There are, like, trees and flowers everywhere.
French: <Glee> <IslandName> est si ... Bonza. Il y a, comme, des arbres et des fleurs partout.
Russian: <Ликования> <IslandName> так ... Bonza. Есть, как, деревья и цветы повсюду.
Chinese: <高兴> <IslandName>是如此...邦扎。还有一样，树木和花草随处可见。
Japanese: <歓喜> <IslandName>そうです...ボンザ。どこでも木々や花は、のように、あります。
<笑>それは圧倒的なのようなものです！

English: <yes>Anyplace you can think of going, there’s a plant that got there first. Trust me.þþ
French: <Oui> Anyplace vous pouvez penser à aller, il y a une plante qui est arrivé là en premier. Croyez-moi.þþ
Russian: <Да> Anyplace вы можете думать, идти, есть завод, который попал туда первым. Поверьте мне.þþ
Chinese: <是>随地你能想到的会，有这么最先到达那里的植物。相信我。þþ
Japanese: <はい>どこでもあなたが最初にそこに着いた所があります、行くことを考えることができます。私を信じて。þþ

English: <proud>I’ve been, like, all over the place.þ
Japanese: <誇り>私はすべての場所で、のような、してきました。þ

English: <shy>I, like, have a confession to make… I didn’t have a Farming Licence until recently…þ
French: <Timide> I, comme, ai une confession à faire ... Je n'ai pas eu une licence de l'agriculture jusqu'à récemment ...þ
Russian: <Застенчивый> Я, вроде бы, есть признание, чтобы сделать ... Я не имел лицензии Farming до недавнего времени ...þ
Chinese: <害羞>我一样，有一个秘密，使...我没有一个养殖许可证直到最近...þ
Japanese: 私は最近まで農業のライセンスを持っていなかった...私は、のように、告白を持っている<敬遠> ...þ

English: I like, didn’t even know it was a thing I needed?þ
French: J'aime, ne savais même pas qu'il était une chose que je besoin?þ
Russian: Мне нравится, даже не знаю, что это было, что я нужен?þ
Chinese: 我很喜欢，甚至不知道这是我需要的东西？þ
Japanese: 私もそれは私が必要との事知りませんでした、好きですか？þ

English: <shy>I was growing plants, like, illegally I guess!þ
French: <Timide> je la culture des plantes, comme, je suppose illégalement!þ
Russian: <Застенчивые> Я выращивание растений, как, незаконно я думаю!þ
Chinese: <害羞>我生长的植物一样，非法我猜！þ
Japanese: <内気>私は成長していた植物は、のような、違法に私は推測します！þ

English: <yes>I like to think of my plants as children.
French: <Oui> Je me plais à penser de mes plantes comme des enfants.
Russian: <Да> Мне нравится думать о моих растениях, как дети.
Chinese: <是>我喜欢把我的植物作为孩子。
Japanese: <はい>私は子供のように私の植物と考えたいです。

Russian: <Ликование> У меня есть, как, огромная семья!
Chinese: <高兴>我一样，一个庞大的家族！
Japanese: <歓喜>私は、のような、巨大な家族を持っています！

French: <Haha> Il est de plus en plus tout le temps!
Japanese: <笑>それはすべての時間を成長しています！

English: I grew up travelling with my family.
French: J'ai grandi voyager avec ma famille.
Russian: Я вырос путешествовать со своей семьей.
Chinese: 我长大了我的家人旅行。
Japanese: 私は家族と一緒に旅行に育ちました。

English: <shy>We were lucky enough to have an <AirShip>. þ
French: <Timide> Nous avons eu la chance d'avoir un <Airship>.þ
Russian: <Застенчивый> Мы были достаточно удачливы, чтобы иметь <AirShip>.þ
Chinese: <害羞>我们很幸运有一个<飞艇>。þ
Japanese: <恥ずかしがり屋>私たちは、<飛行船>持っているのに十分幸運でした。þ

English: <shy>I, like, guess you could say the sky's my home and stuff.þ
French: <Timide> I, comme, crois qu'on peut dire le ciel est ma maison et tout ça.þ
Russian: <Застенчивый> Я, как, думаю, можно сказать, что небо это мой дом и прочее.þ
Chinese: <害羞>我一样，想你可以说天空才是我的家和东西。þ
Japanese: <恥ずかしがり屋>私は、のように、あなたが空の私の自宅とものを言うことができると思います。þ

English: <thinking>Do you ever wonder what the clouds are made of?. þ
French: <Pensée> Avez-vous déjà demandé ce que les nuages ​​sont faits de ?.þ
Russian: <Мышление> Вы когда-нибудь задумывались, что облака сделаны из ?.þ
Chinese: <思考>你永远不知道什么云是由？þ
Japanese: <思考>あなたは今まで雲がで作られているものだろうか？。þ

English: <no>They look like they are soft and fluffy, but like, when you are up there they are, like, not...þ
French: <No> Ils regardent comme ils sont doux et moelleux, mais comme, quand vous êtes en ils sont là, comme, non ...þ
Russian: <Нет> Они выглядят, как они мягкие и пушистые, но как, когда вы там они, вроде бы, не ...þ
Chinese: <编号>他们看起来像他们是柔软，蓬松，但像，当你在那里他们一样，不...þ
Japanese: 彼らはふわふわしているように、<なし>彼らは見えますが、あなたがそこにいるときには、のような、ではない、のような...þ

English: <yes>Even though I, like, spent most of my life in the sky, I feel like I’ve got this special connection to the earth somehow?þ
French: <Oui> Même si je, comme, a passé la majeure partie de ma vie dans le ciel, je me sens comme je l'ai eu ce lien particulier à la terre en quelque sorte?þ
Russian: <Да> Даже если я, как, провел большую часть своей жизни в небе, я чувствую, что я получил эту особую связь с землей каким-то образом?þ
Chinese: <是>即使我一样，度过了我一生中最在天空中，我觉得我已经到了地球不知何故这个特殊的联系？þ
Japanese: 私は何とか地球にこの特別な接続を持っているように、<はい>私は、のように、空に私の人生の大半を費やしたにもかかわらず、私が感じ？þ

English: Do you know what I mean?þ
French: Tu vois ce que je veux dire?þ
Russian: Ты знаешь, что я имею в виду?þ

English: Out of all vegies, I think I like <favouriteFood> the best.
<glee>I could, like, eat them all day.
<thinking>If I’m quiet enough, sometimes it feels like I hear the trees whispering. It’s, like, hard to describe the sound...
French: <Pensée> Si je suis assez calme, parfois il se sent comme je l'entends les arbres chuchotant. Il est, comme, difficile de décrire le son ...
Russian: <Мышление> Если я тихий достаточно, иногда он чувствует, как я слышу деревья шептались. Это, вроде бы, трудно описать звук ...
Chinese: <思考>如果我安静不够，有时感觉就像我听到树木窃窃私语。这是一样，很难形容的声音......
Japanese: <思考>私は静かに十分だ場合、私はささやく木を聞くように、時にはそれが感じています。それは音を記述するために、のような、難しいです...

English: <thinking>It kind of sounds like a gust of air, blowing through the leaves...
French: <Pensée> Ce genre de sons comme une bouffée d'air, soufflant à travers les feuilles ...
Russian: <Мышление> Это своего рода звучит как порыв воздуха, дующий сквозь листву ...
Chinese: <思考>这有点像空气一阵猛烈的声音，透过树叶吹...
Japanese: この種の葉吹き抜ける風の突風のような音の<思考> ...

English: <yes>If you treat your crops with care, feed them and love them, then they will love you back. þþ
French: <Oui> Si vous traitez vos cultures avec soin, les nourrir et les aimer, puis ils vous aimer en retour.þ
Russian: <Да> Если вы лечите свои урожаи с осторожностью, кормить их и любить их, то они будут любить вас.þþ
Chinese: <是>如果你小心对待你的庄稼，喂养他们，爱护他们，那么他们一定会喜欢你。þþ
Japanese: <はい>あなたは注意して、あなたの作物を扱う場合は、それらを供給し、彼らを愛し、そして彼らが戻ってあなたを愛します。þþ

English: <glee>You’ll get back more than you sow!þ
French: <Glee> Vous revenez plus que vous semez!þ
Russian: <Ликования> Вы получите обратно больше, чем вы сеете!þ
Chinese: <高兴>你会得到更多的比你母猪！þ
Japanese: <歓喜>あなたはより多くのあなたが種をまくより返されます！þ

English: <no>A lot of people from <SouthCity> don’t know how to act around <Nomads> like me.þ
French: <No> Beaucoup de gens de <SouthCity> ne savent pas comment agir autour <Nomades> comme moi.þ
Russian: <Нет> Много людей из <SouthCity> не знаю, как действовать вокруг <Кочевники> как я.þ
Chinese: <编号>很多从<SouthCity>人不知道如何行动周围<流浪者>我一样。þ
Japanese: <なし> <SouthCity>から多くの人が私のような<遊牧民>周りに行動する方法がわかりません。þ

English: <haha>They get worried if you don’t know how to, like, fill out their paperwork.þ
French: <Haha> Ils s'inquiéter si vous ne savez pas comment, comme, remplir leurs documents.þ
Russian: <Ха> Они беспокоиться, если вы не знаете, как, например, заполнить свои документы.þ
Chinese: <哈哈>他们担心起来，如果你不知道如何一样，填写自己的文书工作。þ
Japanese: <笑>彼らはあなたが、のように、彼らの書類を記入する方法がわからない場合は心配しています。þ

English: <proud>Let alone if you start talking about the big wide world outside of <SouthCity>!þ
French: <Fiers> Laissez seul si vous commencez à parler du grand monde en dehors de <SouthCity>!þ
Russian: <Горд> Не говоря уже, если вы начинаете говорить о большом мире за пределы <SouthCity>!þ
Chinese: <傲>如果你开始谈论的<SouthCity>阔大世外别说！þ
Japanese: あなたが<SouthCity>の大きな広い世界の外の話を始める場合は、<誇り>おろか！þ

English: <yes>My family and I have been basically everywhere.þ
French: <Oui> Ma famille et moi-même avons été pratiquement partout.þ
Russian: <Да> Моя семья и я были в основном везде.þ
Chinese: <是>我的家人和我已经基本无处不在。þ
Japanese: <はい>私の家族と私は基本的にどこでもされています。þ

English: <thinking>I guess being a <Nomads> I, like, take it for granted…þ
French: <Pensée> Je suppose être un <Nomads> I, comme, prends pour acquis ...þ
Russian: <Мышление> Я думаю, являясь <Кочевников> Я, как, принимаю это как должное ...þ
Chinese: <思考>我猜是一个<流浪者>我一样，想当然...þ
Japanese: <思考>私は<遊牧民> Iであること、のような、許可されたためにそれを取ると思います...þ

English: But not everyone gets to be as lucky as I have been.þ
French: Mais pas tout le monde arrive à être aussi chanceux comme je l'ai été.þ
Russian: Но не каждый может быть так повезло, как я был.þ
Chinese: 但是，并不是每个人都有是一样幸运，因为我一直。þ
Japanese: しかし、誰もが私がされているように幸運のようになります。þ
<恥ずかしがり屋は>私はあまり見てきました！þ

English: <sigh>I just wish I got to hang around a bit longer whenever we landed.þ
French: <Soupir> Je souhaite juste que je suis arrivé à traîner un peu plus à chaque fois que nous avons atterri.þ
Russian: <Вздох> Я просто хочу, чтобы я торчать немного больше, когда мы приземлились.þ
Chinese: <叹>我只希望我有当我们降落流连的时间长一点。þ
Japanese: <ため息>私はちょうど私たちが上陸したときに少し長いたむろするんたいです。þ

English: <yes>Trees can be, like, such crazy characters.þ
French: <Oui> Les arbres peuvent être, comme, ces personnages loufoques.þ
Russian: <Да> Деревья могут быть, например, такие сумасшедшие персонажи.þ
Japanese: <はい>木は、のような、そのような狂気の文字にすることができます。þ

English: <no>They’re always throwing shade and I just can’t help but love them for it. þ
French: <No> Ils sont toujours jeter l'ombre et je ne peux pas aider mais les aimer pour elle.þ
Russian: <Нет> Они всегда бросали тень, и я просто не могу помочь, но любить их за это.þ
Chinese: <编号>他们总是扔遮荫，我不禁爱他们吧。þ
Japanese: <なし>彼らはいつも日陰を投げているし、私は助けることはできませんが、それのためにそれらを愛します。þ

English: <glee>I guess it’s okay when it’s from your friends, right <PlayerName>?þ
French: <Glee> Je pense qu'il est correct quand il est de vos amis, droite <PlayerName>?þ
Russian: <Ликования> Я думаю, что это хорошо, когда это от ваших друзей, верно <PlayerName>?þ
Chinese: <高兴>我想这是好当它从你的朋友的，正确的<PlayerName>？þ
Japanese: <歓喜>私は、右の<プレイヤー名>、それはあなたの友人からだとき、それは大丈夫だと思いますか？þ

English: <thinking>When I was younger, I used to, like, experiment with all kinds of crazy plants. þþ
French: <Pensée> Quand j'étais plus jeune, je habitude, comme autrefois, d'expérimenter avec toutes sortes de plantes folles.þþ
Russian: <Мышление> Когда я был моложе, я использовал, как, экспериментировать со всеми видами сумасшедших растений.þþ
Chinese: <思考>当我年轻的时候，我以前一样，实验用各种疯狂的植物。þþ
Japanese: 私が若かったときに、<思考>、私はクレイジー植物のすべての種類の実験などに使用しました。þþ

English: <yes>Sometimes you have to know what you don’t like before you find out what you do. þ
French: <Oui> Parfois, vous devez savoir ce que vous faites pas comme avant de savoir ce que vous faites.þ
Russian: <Да> Иногда вы должны знать, что вам не нравится, прежде чем узнать, что вы делаете.þ
Chinese: <是>有时候，你必须知道你做了什么不喜欢你发现你做什么了。þ

For a long long time I felt like I was just treading water and waiting for something big to happen.þ
<no>You really can’t be like that though.þ
<thinking>Not if you want to be happy.þ
<proud>You have to MAKE things happen yourself!
It’s funny how things change when you get older...þþ
<shy>I look back at times I felt embarrassed, and they just make me chuckle now.þ
Things I cared about so much can just seem silly.þ
Time can really put things into perspective, don’t you think?þ
The rough stuff gets sanded over, but the bright stuff shines even brighter!
I’ll tell you what, saving up for all these years, I would have never imagined seeing <IslandName> look like this again.þ
<yes>While it’s not exactly how I remember it, it feels nice knowing that <IslandName> is someone's home again.þ
I think my Father would be very proud of what we’ve done here, <PlayerName>.þ
You’re the best thing that ever happened to me, <PlayerName>.þ
Sometimes I keep myself up late at night imagining that someone else responded to that ad...þ
<no>But I’ll tell you what, there is no point in thinking like that!þ
My father always used to say: “You keep your friends close, and your best friends closer.”þ
<haha> He wasn’t much of a wordy, but he knew how to get things done, make no mistake.þ
<yes>Always looking out for his friends, he was.þ
So, you wanted to talk about your home?
I want to move my house.

Japanese: さてさて、その後、<プレイヤー名>。

English: Ah! So, you're interested in applying for a house deed?
I'll just let you know there is a <getHousePrice> up front fee. <thinking>
Oh, and once you've applied for the deed, you will have to source the construction materials yourself. <yes>
So, are you interested in applying for a house of your own?
I want to apply for a house.
Well, I'll let you have a think about it.
Let me know if you change your mind.
What exactly can I help you with?
French: Qu'est-ce exactement ce que je peux vous aider?
Japanese: 何が丁度私があなたを助けることができますか？
私は行為を見ることができますか？

English: I want to move a building.
Japanese: 私は建物を移動したいです。

English: Lets see what we can do...
French: Permet de voir ce que nous pouvons faire ...
Russian: Давайте посмотрим, что мы можем сделать ...
Japanese: 私たちは何ができるか見てみましょう...

Russian: Разговор снова в ближайшее время, хорошо?

English: <thinking>Moving the building can be a bit expensive...
French: <Pensée> Déplacement du bâtiment peut être un peu cher ...
Russian: <Мышление> Перемещение здания может быть немного дороже ...
Japanese: <思考>建物を移動すると、少し高価になることができます...

English: <yes>Let's get that town debt payed off before we move any buildings, okay?
French: <Oui> get de Let que la dette de la ville a payé avant de nous déplacer tous les bâtiments, d'accord?
Russian: <Да> прибудет Давайте, что город задолженность выплачивается, прежде чем перемещать любые здания, хорошо?
Japanese: <はい>、我々はすべての建物を移動する前に、町の借金は大丈夫、オフ払っていることレッツ・ゲット？

English: Although this isn’t the <IslandName> I remember, it's still amazing seeing the changes you’ve made around here <PlayerName>.þ
I think my father would be proud of us!þ
Remember back when you were setting tents up for us both?þ
You’ve done such a good job, I’ll tell you what!þ
I’ll tell you what, it really warms my heart to see <IslandName> bustling again.þ
Things are really shaping up around here, thanks to you!þ
<no>I would have never imagined seeing <IslandName> looking like this again..þ
<boohoo>You’ve really made an old woman very happy, <PlayerName>.þ
Well, to make your house bigger its going to cost <getHousePrice> .  How does that sound?
...Oh. It seems like you a bit short on cash. <shy>
Perhaps you can come back when your pockets are a bit heavier?
Well, if you change your mind, please come speak to me.
Well, to make your house bigger its going to cost <getHousePrice>. How does that sound?
Okay. We'll set up a construction box infront of your house. <yes>
We wont be able to start construction until you fill the box with the required construction materials. <yes>
As so you as have all the required materials, construction can begin!
You'll find the construction material box in front of your house.
As soon as it's full you'll find the construction will be completed over night.
Don't worry. I hire very quiet workers. You won't hear a peep out of them! <haha>
I hope you're looking forward to your new house! <glee>

Japanese: 私たちは<relocateBuildingName>移転するつもりだそう？

English: Relocating the building will put the town <sprite=11>25,000 in debt.
French: Déménager le bâtiment mettra la ville <sprite = 11> 25 000 dans la dette.
Russian: Переселение здания поставит город <спрайта = 11> 25,000 в долге.
Japanese: 建物の再配置は、債務の<スプライト= 11> 25,000の町を入れます。
のは、それを移動してみましょう！

English: Here is the <itemName>. Place it down in the new place we want the <relocateBuildingName>.
French: Voici le <itemName>. Placez-le dans le nouveau lieu, nous voulons que le <relocateBuildingName>.
Russian: Вот <ITEMNAME>. Поместите его вниз на новом месте мы хотим <relocateBuildingName>.
Japanese: ここで、<itemNameに>です。私たちは<relocateBuildingName>たい新しい場所にそれを下に置きます。

English: <yes>The building will be moved over night.
French: <Oui> Le bâtiment sera déplacé pendant la nuit.
Russian: <Да> Здание будет перемещено в течение ночи.
Japanese: <はい>建物は夜の上に移動されます。
問題ありません、<プレイヤー名>。

English: <yes>We've got an animal in here already waiting for you to take them to their new home...
Why don't you take any animals in their boxes outside first?
<glee>Then we can talk about giving them a new friend.
Welcome to Irwin's Barn. How can I help?
<yes>I want you to take this as a reward!

Japanese: これはとても素晴らしいです！

English: <yes>I've popped <animalJustBoughtName> in this animal box. Please take her to new home and release her.
French: <Pompé> S'il vous plaît prendre soin de <animalJustBoughtName>.
Japanese: <汲み上げ> <animalJustBoughtName>の世話をしてください。

Russian: <Громко рыдать или смеяться> Я буду скучать по ней!
Japanese: <boohoo>私は彼女を欠場するつもりです！

English: I think <NPCName> is such a sweetheart.þ
<no>Plants are nice and all, but they just can’t appreciate you the way animals can.þ
<yes><NPCName> is really open minded when it comes to purchases.
<sigh>It can be a tough grind talking to <NPCName> sometimes...þ
<yes>Must be tough for him being that much of a smarty pants, I reckon.þ
<shy>Hearing <NPCName> talk about his wife makes me a little weepy sometimes.þ
There’s some crazy styles over at <NPCName>'s shop!þ
I’d love to dress up like a pirate, but I don’t wanna scare the <animalName>s!þ
You’re <PlayerName>, right?þ Absolutely wonderful to meet you, mate!
<haha>I’m <myName>! Oh, I already told you that, right?þ
I’m visiting <IslandName> trying to find a home for some beautiful little creatures.þ
If you have a <AnimalHandlingLicence> come by and talk to me.þ
<glee>There’s nothing more bonza than looking after a beautiful little creature!þ
<yes>I hope you can help me out, <PlayerName>.þ
<glee>And <NPCName> still has a surprise for us!þ
She told me she had a special <Snag> for everyone!
<thinking>You reckon the animals around <IslandName> are bothered by it?þ
<glee>I doubt it, they are probably loving it too.þ
Hey <PlayerName>. I actually have a confession to make.þ
<no>You see, I had been adopting all the animals the people in <SouthCity> couldn’t look after anymore...þ
<thinking>I guess you could say that it all fell apart when the neighbour under me complained about all the noise coming from my apartment...þ
<haha>He said it sounded like a zoo in there!þ He was kind of right about that!þ
<pumped>So when I left, I told myself I would make a big change and move on to a better place!þ
<haha>I guess it’s not all bad, because now I get to look after all the fluffy and furry animals I want!
You know why the animals I have in my store need a good home to go to?þ
<boohoo>People buy these beautiful animals from dodgy traders back in <SouthCity>.þ
<no>The people that buy then don’t seem to realise that the little beauties eventually get bigger!
Or that they need things like food and water.þ
<boohoo>Not to mention that they need love!þ
<proud>So I take them off their hands and pay the <Dinks> needed to ship them to me.þ
That’s the only reason I charge a fee for the absolutely beautiful little critters.þ
<glee>For every one that I sell, I can afford to find another one a home too!þ
<pumped>You can say whatever you want to them and they will barely interrupt you!
Don’t you just think <animalName> are so cute!þþ
They are so little and fluffy!þ
<yes>They've got big hearts you know?þ Three of them in fact!þ
<animalName> wool is some of the softest wool in the world. þ
<haha>It might have something to do with the fact that it's nearly always wet.þ
<pumped>Crikey! þDo those critters love the water!þ
<glee>They are loyal, loving and struth, are they cute.þ
Oh, and did I mention they are loyal?þ
<haha>Oh, what about how cute they are?þ
<no>I wasn’t really allowed to have any pets growing up in <SouthCity>.þ
<pumped>The <animalName> you find up in the tropical parts of the island can be really fierce!þ
<yes>I'd keep my distance from their nests if I was you.þ
<pumped>They've got razor sharp claws and are just brimming with attitude!þ
<no>I don't get how some people don't like animals.
Some are slimy, some are poisonous and some even have crackin big teeth!
Have you ever gotten a gander of those <animalName>, mate?
A lot of people have told me that the <BlobFish> back in <SouthCity> was terrible.þ
<no>I never could bring myself to eat them.þ
<proud>I reckon I’ve got one of the best noses in the world. þ
<yes>Everybody’s always telling me how good it is.
They always say “<myName>, you really smell, mate”þ
<yes>I could watch animals all day long.
<haha>They’re just always doing something, even when they’re not doing anything.
<thinking>Hmmm, if I could choose to be any animal in the world, huh?þ
<thinking>I reckon, if I really thought about it... it would definitely have to be...
<yes>Being a great animal handler is all about respect.
<haha>Sometimes you’ve really got to respect the fact that some animals just do NOT wanna be handled.þ
<glee>There are so many critters… crittering around!þ
<SouthCity> didn’t really have any interesting wildlife, you know.þ
<yes>Growing up all I ever wanted to do was look after animals that were in need.þ
<glee>I don’t know what it is, but I just bloody love all creatures, great and small!þ
Don’t you just love being outdoors?
The sun on your back, the wind in your hair.
<thinking>A lot of what I know about animals is maybe a bit outdated these days..þ
I learnt it mostly through the books I found in <SouthCity>.þ
<yes>But seeing an animal in real life is totally different to reading about it in a book.þ
<thinking>I mean, the <animalName> I read about in books doesn’t even have horns!þ
<no>I’ve never been that fond of bugs.þ
They’re is just nothing cute about them!þ
<no>I just can’t see why so many people like to keep them as pets back in <SouthCity>.þ
<angry>Oh and they have too many legs!þ
I reckon I’ve had some real friendships with animals, <PlayerName>.þ
<sigh>But maybe they aren’t real friendships if they can’t talk back…þ
<shy>Maybe I need to talk to people more!þ
And it’s good for you too!þ
<pumped>That stuff will build up your bones really good!þ
<yes>One of those can feed a whole family back in <SouthCity>.þ
<yes>That’s why people will pay top <Dink> for them.þ
<thinking>Although, they are super delicate and can be hard to transport.þ
<pumped>They have a sac in the back of their throat that can spit a flammable liquid!þ
<thinking>Not quite sure how they light it up though!þ
<yes>They can be scary for sure, but I think they are beautiful animals in their own way!þ
<yes><animalName> horns can be valuable back in <SouthCity>.þ
<no>Posh people like to use them for cutlery handles and the like.þ
<yes>They’re better off just being left on their heads!þ
The one insect I can get behind is the humble <itemName>.þ
<glee>Not only are they cute, but they make honey!þ
<haha>What a sweet thing for a bug to do!þ
<animalName> are funny little critters, don’t you think?þ
<haha>They’re slow even when they are trying to be fast.þ
Those little guys make me laugh when they run!þ
<animalName> have an absolutely beautiful song, don’t you think?þ
<glee>Those little guys sing their hearts out.þ
<thinking>I don’t think I’ve heard anything like it before, to be honest.þ
Hey <PlayerName>, thank you for being such a good friend!þ
I’m so glad I came here to <IslandName>.þ
<yes>I think my life has really changed for the better after meeting you.þ
I don’t think I’ve ever had a friend like you before, <PlayerName>.þþ
<yes>I mean, I’ve had some good mates who were animals.þ
<shy>But it’s always good to have a mate that can chat back!þ
<yes>I’m constantly AMAZED by all the things animals can do.þ
<worried>Nature can be a bit harsh sometimes, or vicious!þ
Animals didn’t do anything to deserve the <Shifts>...þ
They were just minding their own business whilst people mucked everything up.þ
<no>It sucks that others have to pay for our mistakes...þ
<no>Thing is, I don’t think folk in <SouthCity> even know what they’re missing out on.þ
<pumped>Having a gander at all of this though, they’d be blown away, I reckon!
<thinking>I’d love to have everything in one place one day.þ
A few of each animal type from all over the world, in one location!þ
Not behind glass or cooped up or anything… we’d make proper enclosures and environments!þ
They’d have all the room they needed AND all of their favourite foods.þ
I reckon we’d take better care of nature if everybody saw how beautiful it could be.
<IslandName> is well on the way to being a great place! þ
<yes>You should be very proud of yourself, <PlayerName>.þ
<glee>I hope you keep up the great work!þ
<IslandName> is changing for the better, and it’s all because of your hard work, <PlayerName>!
Have I told you how great <IslandName> is looking lately?þ
<pumped>You’ve obviously been putting a lot of work into making this town great, and it’s looking absolutely beautiful, mate!þ
<IslandName> is looking absolutely beautiful thanks to you, <PlayerName>.þ
It’s amazing the transformation that this place has gone under.þ
I can barely recognise the place.þ

Japanese: シーズキューティー、右？

English: If you've got a good home for her, she's all yours for <buyItemPrice>.
French: Si vous avez une bonne maison pour elle, elle est tout à vous pour <buyItemPrice>.
Russian: Если у вас есть хороший дом для нее, она все твое для <buyItemPrice>.
Japanese: あなたが彼女のために良い家庭を持っていれば、彼女は<buyItemPrice>のためにすべてのあなたです。

English: But you don't have an empty coop for her to stay in!
French: Mais vous ne disposez pas d'une coop vide pour elle de rester!
Russian: Но у вас нет пустой курятник для нее, чтобы остаться в!
Japanese: しかし、あなたは彼女に滞在するための空の小屋を持っていません！

English: A <buyItemName> like her needs a coop to stay safe. <yes>
French: A <buyItemName> comme elle a besoin d'une cage pour rester en sécurité. <Oui>
Russian: А <buyItemName> как она нуждается в курятник оставаться в безопасности. <Да>
Japanese: A <buyItemName>彼女が安全に滞在するために小屋を必要とするような。 <はい>

English: Craft a house for her and place it down somewhere. Once you've done that come back and speak to me. <yes>
French: Craft une maison pour elle et le placer quelque part. Une fois que vous avez fait revenir et me parler. <Oui>
Russian: Крафт дом для нее, и поместить его куда-то вниз. После того, как вы сделали, что вернуться и поговорить со мной. <Да>
Japanese: 彼女のために家を作ると、どこかの下に置きます。あなたが完了したら戻ってくると私に話しています。 <はい>

English: That's okay! I'm sure she'll find a home soon! <yes>
French: C'est bon! Je suis sûr qu'elle va trouver une maison bientôt! <Oui>
Russian: Это нормально! Я уверен, что она будет найти дом в ближайшее время! <Да>
Japanese: 大丈夫！私は彼女がすぐに家を見つけることができます確信しています！ <はい>
シーズキューティー、右？

English: If you've got a good home for her, she's all yours for <buyItemPrice>.
French: Si vous avez une bonne maison pour elle, elle est tout à vous pour <buyItemPrice>.
Russian: Если у вас есть хороший дом для нее, она все твое для <buyItemPrice>.
Japanese: あなたが彼女のために良い家庭を持っていれば、彼女は<buyItemPrice>のためにすべてのあなたです。

English: Wait, you don't have enough money... <shy>
French: Attendez, vous n'avez pas assez d'argent ... <timide>
Russian: Подождите, у вас нет достаточно денег ... <застенчивый>
Japanese: 待って、あなたは十分なお金を持っていない... <恥ずかしがり屋>

English: If you can get it together she will be here waiting for you all day!
French: Si vous pouvez l'obtenir ensemble, elle sera là pour vous attendre toute la journée!
Russian: Если вы можете получить его вместе, она будет здесь ждет вас в течение всего дня!
Japanese: あなたが一緒にそれを得ることができれば、彼女は一日中あなたを待ってここになります！

English: That's okay! I'm sure she'll find a home soon! <yes>
French: C'est bon! Je suis sûr qu'elle va trouver une maison bientôt! <Oui>
Russian: Это нормально! Я уверен, что она будет найти дом в ближайшее время! <Да>
Japanese: 大丈夫！私は彼女がすぐに家を見つけることができます確信しています！ <はい>

English: Can I interest you in a little trim?
Okay, what can do with your "doo" today? <haha>
A haircut or colour change is <sprite=11>5000.
<glee>If you would like a haircut I could always use the practice!þ
I’m having a bloody bonza day, <PlayerName>.þ
I hope you got a <Snag> while they were still hot!þ
It’s going to be a great day, full of tunes, sun and some bloody beautiful <Snags>.
<NPCName> made me a rippa of a <Snag>!þ
<no>Everything I cook usually ends up with some hair in it.þ
<yes>At least I know it’s not my own hair.þ
My family would never let me near their hair.
<no>They said that I'd always cut something of theirs that wasn't hair.
<haha>Did they not know that looking good can sometimes hurt?
<thinking>Back when I was studying to be a chef I would always cut my fingers.
<haha>I'm just not that great at using anything sharp!
I worked in the coal mines back in <SouthCity> for a few years...
<yes>I use to cut some of my friends hair while we were down there.
Everyone said they loved what I did…
<boohoo>Until we all came back up into the light...
<shy>I tend to get a bit shaky when I get nervous.
<shy>I mean, that would be okay if I didn't get so nervous when I was giving haircuts!
<glee>And just like clothes, the way you style it can show off your personality!
<thinking>I've been thinking about dying my hair.
<yes>I've been pretty happy with myself lately, <PlayerName>. þ
<proud>I haven't cut anyone's ear off or anything since I started visiting <IslandName>.þ
<thinking>Before I was a hairdresser I had a part-time job as a pet stylist.
<glee>It's where I learnt my best cuts and styles!
<yes>They’re amazing innovative styles, so nobody asks for them a second time.
Have you ever tried cutting topiaries?
<yes>You should totally do it if you get the chance.
<haha>It's wonderfully fun and the plants don't even complain when you mess it up!
<yes>I've had a lot of jobs before I settled on hairstylist.
<yes>My parents told me to do what I was good at.
<proud>But I think that's just too easy!
<thinking>Hey, <PlayerName>, I was thinking about taking on an apprentice...
Maybe they could teach me a thing or two?
<yes>The best thing about hair is that it grows back, so we can always try again.
<shy>Not that we’ll need to! It’s just nice to have some backup options.
But, have you considered going bald, <PlayerName>?
<proud>I am, without a doubt, the absolute best hairdresser here on <IslandName>.
<haha>I mean, honestly, it’s not even close!
<yes>Some of my best customers pay me NOT to cut their hair.
<pumped>My whole life people have been trying to take sharp objects away from me, but look at me now!
<shy>I’m so, so sorry, <PlayerName>. I don’t know what came over me.
People back in <SouthCity> generally went for the boring haircuts.
<yes>So it's nice to be doing something different here on <IslandName>.
<pumped>Give me any two pieces and I can make em fit together no problem!
<thinking>I think a <animalName> would make excellent hairdresser.
<yes>With their sharp jagged teeth and persistent attitude, they have all the right qualities.
<worried>I really hope one of them doesn’t open up a shop around here, or I’d be out of business!
<no>Don’t let anybody ever tell you that you can’t do something.
<no>Even if you have none of the skills, or are poorly suited, or are physically incapable, it doesn’t matter!

Japanese: 私のああ！ A <donationName>！ <ショック>

French: Notre collection est actuellement un manque <donationName>. <Timide>
Russian: Наша коллекция в настоящее время отсутствует <donationName>. <Застенчивый>
Japanese: 私達のコレクションは現在、<donationName>が欠落しています。 <恥ずかしがり屋>

English: Would you be willing to donate it?
Japanese: あなたはそれを寄付することをいとわないだろうか？
あなたの寛大さは抜群です！ <歓喜>

English: Please accept <donationReward> as a small token of our gratitude!
Oh, I'll give this back then.
French: Oh, je vais donner cette époque.
Japanese: ああ、私は、この背中を与えるでしょう。

English: If you change your mind, don't hesitate to come back.
French: Si vous changez d'avis, ne pas hésiter à revenir.
Russian: Если вы передумаете, не колеблясь, чтобы вернуться.
Japanese: あなたがあなたの心を変更する場合は、戻ってくることを躊躇しません。

English: Is there anything else I can help you with?
French: Y at-il autre chose que je peux vous aider?
Russian: Есть ли что-нибудь еще я могу помочь?
Japanese: 私はあなたを助けることができる何か他のものはありますか？

Russian: У меня есть еще одно пожертвование.
Japanese: 私は別の寄付を持っています。

English: Oh? What else have you got?
Russian: Ой? Что еще у вас есть?
Japanese: ああ？あなたは他に何を持っていますか？
<プレイヤー名>、ありがとうございました。

English: <shy>I would shake your hand in thanks, but that might be inappropriate.
That's one of our empty frames.
French: C'est un de nos cadres vides.
Russian: Это один из наших пустых кадров.
Japanese: それが私たちの空のフレームの一つです。

English: Oh! Do you have a photo we could put here?
French: Oh! Avez-vous une photo que nous pourrions mettre ici?
Russian: Ой! У вас есть фото мы могли бы поставить здесь?
Japanese: ああ！あなたは私たちがここに置くことができる写真を持っていますか？

English: Great! Show me what you want to place here.
French: Génial! Montrez-moi ce que vous voulez placer ici.
Russian: Большой! Покажите мне, что вы хотите разместить здесь.
Japanese: すごい！あなたがここに置きたいものを見せてください。

English: Well, if you take a great photo you want to show off. Please bring it in!
French: Eh bien, si vous prenez une grande photo que vous voulez montrer. S'il vous plaît le mettre en!
Russian: Ну, если взять большую фотографию, которую вы хотите показать. Пожалуйста, возьмите это!
Japanese: あなたは素晴らしい写真を撮る場合さて、あなたは披露したいと思います。で、それを持参してください！

English: Oh! What a wonderful photo that is!
French: Oh! Quelle merveilleuse photo qui est!
Russian: Ой! Какая замечательная фотография, что есть!
Japanese: ああ！何が素晴らしい写真！

English: If you have another photo to you want to place here let me know!

English: <shy>I don't think I introduced myself... I get a bit carried away sometimes.

<thinking>Maybe that’s the surprise <NPCName> has for us tonight!þ
<no>I’m not even going to step foot into the Museum today.þ

I’ve never seen something so amazing.þ
<yes>This is the best <Snag> I’ve ever had.þ

<shy>I see you have quite a few new amazing specimens not yet in our museum!
Would you be willing to donate all of these?
Please accept <donationReward> as a small token of our gratitude!
Oh, I'll give these back then.
If you change your mind, don't hesitate to come back.
<shy>I see you have quite a few new amazing specimens not yet in our museum!

English: Imagine if we just kept all the old stuff where we found it?
<worried>It would be all over the place!
<yes>I’ve really been enjoying documenting all the new species on this island.
<glee>To tell you the truth though, filing the documentation is nearly as enjoyable!
<worried>Fish and bugs are very interesting, but I really don't like touching either...
<proud>After all, things in a museum are for looking at, not touching.
<thinking>I’ve been wondering if there could be a way to catalogue air?
Would you be interested in seeing an air exhibit, <PlayerName>?
<glee> See, I had a feeling you were a fellow air-head!

<sigh>þAh, that’s a shame. I’ve already collected a bunch of specimens in some jars...

<yes>If you ever take a great photo and you want to show it off, please come and display it in the museum.
<yes>Don't worry, I will fill out the required forms for you!
<proud>It’s so great to have a one stop shop to look at all the interesting stuff around here.
<glee>There are so many new species to study here on <IslandName>!
<no>I don’t mean I’m going to cut them open!
<proud>Here at the <IslandName> museum we only study by observing!
<thinking>Imagine if we could take everything on <IslandName> and put it in a museum!
<proud>That way, when people wanted to see a certain thing, they could just make their way to that wing!
Studying things is just my job.
<glee>For example, in my spare time I like to talk about all the things I’ve been studying.
<thinking>I think one day we’ll see a Museum of Museums.
All that knowledge, all those exhibits, all that paperwork!
<thinking>I'd love to experience some more travelling one day.
<no>As long as I don't have to actually go anywhere else, of course.
<pumped>We could get exhibits from all over the world, and bring them right to <IslandName>!
<worried>There’s not enough order out there so it can get a bit overwhelming.
<worried>All the plants and people and animals are just going around doing whatever they want, all over the place!
<thinking>There’s so many different ways to organise things and group them together.
<yes>Playing around with them can be exciting.
<pumped>Sometimes I’ll go around and rearrange everything alphabetically, then by height, and sometimes even by smell!
<yes>That last one is really easy to do, because everything smells like disinfectant, like it should.þ
<shy>Sometimes I like to climb into an empty case and pretend I’M the exhibit.
<haha>I’m a perfect candidate too, because I never try and escape.
<shy>Sometimes I stand really really still and pretend I’m a statue...
Just a little museum humour for you, <PlayerName>.
<thinking>It must be nice to be getting watched all day.
<worried>I don’t think I could handle the attention though.
<thinking>Though, maybe if people formed an orderly queue it wouldn’t freak me out so much?
<no>I don’t listen to it, of course, it’s far too noisy.
But there’s so many different ways to catalogue and arrange it.
<thinking>You can organise by artist, genre, length, beats per minute…
<yes>Perfect weather to be indoors and studying!
<glee>I just love the smell of fresh paper.
<yes>All neatly arranged, lined up and ready for work.
<pumped>Sometimes I feel bad writing on it, but we're doing really important work here.
What’s the point of anything happening if nobody is there to record it?
<yes>Hey, <PlayerName>, if a tree falls in the woods, please be sure to let me know.

Just because you like everything on the menu doesn’t mean you need to order it all at once, <petName>.þ
<no>Oh, there’s stuff I’d probably never eat again though.þ
<proud>That’s what life’s for, I reckon. Trying things.þ
<haha>I’m here for a good time, not a long time!þ
<proud>You’ll never catch me behind a desk, that’s for sure.
<no>Day in day out watching the clock, growing old miserably.þ
<shy>I guess I don’t need to tell you though!þ
I see you with your little legs always running all over the place.
<yes>Always scurrying around here and there, foraging and thwacking things.þ
<thinking>I’ve always been the busy type. I just like working, I think.þþ
<no>There wasn’t much work in <SouthCity>, or at least, none that mattered to anybody. þ
<yes>I feel like I’m doing that now though, <petName>.
We’re making a difference here, eh?
You can have all the planning and preparation in the world.
<pumped>But sooner or later you’ve got to actually knuckle down and get things done.
That’s what I like about you, <PlayerName>.
It’s all well and good being a little harsh at times.
<no>There’s no point being mean just for the sake of it though, and you’ve gotta expect a little back.þ
<proud>I says, don’t be afraid of speaking your mind, but don’t be surprised when somebody doesn’t wanna hear it either.þ
<no>You don’t have to love what you do for a living, we’re all just trying to get by.þ
<yes>You should absolutely find something you love doing though.þ
<shy>Something you can put your whole heart and soul into, yeah?þ
<thinking>I reckon everybody’s passionate about something or other.þ
<yes>Do what you want, I reckon, as long as you’re not hurting anybody.þ
I tell you, ever since I’ve been here, it’s like a fog’s been lifted.þþ
<proud>I’m making some of the best feeds I reckon I ever have.þ
<yes>It’s definitely easier when you’ve got ingredients to work with!þ
You know, you’re probably my favourite customer. þ
You don’t say much, you always pay your bills, and you’re always ready to lend an ear.þ
I reckon we mate a cracking great team, <petName>.
I used to hear stories when I was little about what the world outside was like.
<no>I don’t think I ever paid too much attention at first.
I figured they were just stories to pass the time.þ
<yes>Turns out most of them were right, the good and the bad.þ
I guess you can’t have one without the other, right, <petName>?þ
Sure, you could make what I sell yourself.
You’d have to wait all year, mind.þ
It might even taste similar, if you’re lucky.
<no>It’s never going to be the same though.þ
<pumped>The stuff I sell is made with blood, sweat and tears.þ
It’s been absolutely chockers at my place lately.þ
<glee>I can’t thank you enough for letting me liven <IslandName> up!þ
<no>Big city folk just don’t get it, I reckon.þ
They’ve got their steel, their concrete, their paperwork… and that’s it!þ
<shy>You’ve gotta make time for your friends, yeah?þ
<yes>They’re the ones that’ll pull you out of the muck, or listen when you need a good whinge. þ
I feel like you get it, <PlayerName>, I really do.þ
<shy>I had my head in the clouds when I was younger. þ
<thinking>I was always dreaming of finer foods.þ
<pumped>Just wholesome simple tucker that could fill your belly and keep you fighting fit.þ
<shy>It’s easy to dream. Doesn’t cost you a <Dink>.þ
<proud>Putting all this together took some hard yakka though, if I say so myself.þ
Thanks to you, I reckon I can get you the best tucker on <IslandName>! þ
We’d get traders from time to time back in <SouthCity>.
It was the only time we ever saw or ate anything different.þ
<proud>I’ll tell you, the first time I ever ate a slice of roo meat… it was like my whole world opened up.þ
<pumped>So tender, so juicy. I never knew what taste even was before then!þ
<no>Of course, the folks in charge would always shut them down right quick, but it didn’t matter.þ
<pumped>I knew I needed to get out.þ
There’s nobody to watch your back out in the big city.
<no>If you fall down there, you’ll go right on getting trampled.þ
<pumped>Just try and trample us here, I reckon!
You can’t always trust people, <PlayerName>, but you can always trust them to be themselves.þþ
As long as you keep that in mind, nothing will surprise you, I reckon.þ
Anyway, I like you <petName>, but I’ve got work to do!þ
<proud>I worked hard to get where I am, I did.
<yes>There was always someone there telling me I couldn’t do it.þ
I didn’t have a head for business, they says.
<no>My cooking was trash, they says, blah blah blah blah.þ
<angry>I’d had just about enough of it, so I says, stuff that, and stuff you too!þ
<proud>Sooner or later you’ve got to just ignore the whingers and take charge of yourself.þ
You should listen, <PlayerName>, I bloody wish I did sooner!þ
You’re a good egg, <PlayerName>, I mean that.þ
<shy>I appreciate you taking the time to listen to me natter on.þ
<haha>Most times I’d be nattering regardless, but it’s nice to have somebody listen!þ
You let me know if you need anything, <petName>.þ
You ever wonder about all that junk buried beneath the surface?þ
You reckon someone left it there or what?þ
I like to think it was the <animalName>. Nah, hear me out!þ
They had all these fancy machines, yeah? All these whirring and buzzing things and what-have-you.þ
Well, they’ve got them all going full bull at all hours, right?þ
Well, <animalName> bossman is cranky now. The head <animalName> or whatever, Top Dog.þ
He can’t get to sleep, see, on account of all the ruckus.þ
So one day he says, “Oi, youse!”, he says, “Pack that in, the lot of you!”þ
They bury heaps of it, they do. So’s they can focus on all the regular important <animalName> stuff.þ
Like, um, burying and sniffing and running and all that malarky.þ
<no>I’d like to say I was great at rustling up tucker straight from the word Go, but that wouldn’t be true.þ
<shy>Nah mate, I burned more than a few <itemName> to get here, I did.þ
<pumped>Ate every single one of them too! Builds character.þ
Only way to learn, I reckon. þ
<shy>Nah, I burnt a salad first time I tried it!þ
Look at all these really, really cute bugs!
<no>I'll give these tasty items back to you then.
